item.title: Proxxon Micromot 12V tools socket / plug for panel mount
item.description:
This is a plug shell for Proxxon Micromot series of tools, which operate on 12V power.

It has 2 halves which bolt together (4mm bolt fits in the hole), and for contacts, it uses butt connectors (without the plastic sleeve), similiar to https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3437152

The butt connectors should be solid all the way around (so not have a split to help crush them), and be a tight fit around the tools plugs poles.

I used butt connectors called "VT STV-B Butt connector, 1.5 - 2.5 mm²", bough from here: https://www.reichelt.com/de/en/butt-connector-1-5-2-5-mm-blue-vt-stv-b-p231400.html, however, there must be similiar connectors available elsewhere too, you might want to test others before ordering those if you find the shipping expensive.

The plug is designed to slide into a slot in a panel. I have however included the .blend file as well if you want to edit this more easily.
item.author: Okxa

item.title: Hotend adapter Creality CR6 SE to CR 10 / ENDER 3
item.description:
Due to the low availability of spare parts for CR6 i decided to make myself an adapter for hotend that i can mount hotend from creality cr 10. I have never done such things so process was very long and the result is awful, but it works! Works really well, my printer is making much better prints than before.

Dont do supports inside screw holes!

There are holes to mount a fan, but i found it works better when i mount fan on the hotend case.

I printed it using standard PLA, with ABS, adapter for sure will last much longer :)

Fell free to improve this model, he really needs this!

I used 0.4mm nozzle, i dont know if holes for screws dont gonna be to big with smaller nozzles.

item.title: Multi-function woodworking tool
item.description:
A multi-function woodworking tool (for left and right handed)

  • scribing ruler
  • 22.5, 45, 67.5 and 90 degree square
  • saw guide for cutting at 22.5, 45, 67.5 and 90 degrees

The saw guide is particularly suitable for Japanese saws (kataba style for example).

There are four parts to print

1 The main body with the ruler (support needed under the thread)
The thread can be reinforced with a M5 screw of at least 35 mm if necessary. You can also increase infill percent in the thread.

2 The ruler which can be glued under the body (position according to left/right hand) without support

3 The nut without support

4 The saw guide with a support at the hole.
There are two saw guides provided.
One for blades under 50 mm and one for blades under 70 mm. Choose according to your saw.

item.title: Zonestar P802Q series z-bottom fix bracket
item.description: Zonestar P802Q series is a 3d printer that is one of "clones" of Prusa i3 with stainless frame. The stainless bracket of z-axes of those printers' fixes only the stepper motors but the z linear shafts are in holes drilled on the brackets. The diameter of the hole is greater than the shaft about 0.5mm so the shaft moves in all directions. This parts is a remix of "z-axis-bottom.stl" on https://www.prusaprinters.org/prints/57217-i3-mk3s-printable-parts/files .

item.title: Detent Marks for Virpil WarBRD
item.description:
Like if you do. Comment for improvement.

Please go to Thing Files and download each part separately.

This modification is part in the joystick add-on series.

This system add detent marks to the Virpil WarBRD base. I designed them to get a tactile feedback when the stick wanders outside of the normal flight envelope of the aircraft.

Applicability:

  • Compatible with the Virpil WarBRD joystick base.

Options:

  • Detent marks:
    • 1 in the center.
    • 1 at one extremity ("AFterBurner").
    • 2 at both edges.
    • 2 midway.
    • 3 = combination of a 1-mark upper part and a 2-mark bottom (with the logo) part.

Print:

  • No support required.
  • Designed for filament printing, since resin isn't flexible enough.
  • Printed in PLA.
  • Trim the "elephant leg" off the parts, if any.

Assembly:

  1. Remove both cams, the spacers and the extension spring. → Virpil's video on Youtube.
  2. Install a 3D-printed spacer, an upper and a bottom detent part instead of the metallic spacers.
  3. Put the cam assembly inside the base back in place without the metallic spacers.

Known Issues and Planned Solutions:

  • Installing them on the X-axis would require to replace the cam bolts with longer ones. (Untested yet)


Use the referral code STAR-TQTV-6RL5 to get 5000UEC when creating a new account for Star Citizen.

item.title: Wanhao D6/MPMU M8 Probe Remix for 4020 Fanduct
item.description:
Thanks to RedEyedRaven for the initial design and intinify1976 for their remix.

This is basically a mashup of the two but I made the nozzle bottoms flat for better printability and added a mount to hold a M8 inductive probe. Also went and did a section analysis to see the inside of the duct and clean up the internals a bit. Should be a perfectly smooth inside now with no artifacts.

It's way too hard to fit a 5015 in the MPMU without sacrificing build volume. Empiricus's remix is the best I've seen but the 50 dollar 5015 is a hard pill to swallow. The 4020 should be more than enough and will still push more air than the stock configuration and even dual 4010 noctuas.

Probe offset should be
X: 40.8
Y: -14.1

Follow 1bigpig's wiring diagram here and firmware tutorial for getting the M8 probe installed. You will need a springsteel pei bed to make sure the inductive probe triggers correctly.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2081168

Ideally print in ABS or better, PETG should probably work if you use the model with supports. You will also need to add supports to make sure the probe mount prints correctly.

item.title: G39 (G36) WE 999c IdZ GBB SL-9 Like Stock expansion
item.description:
Hello there,

Couldn't find any SL-8 / SL-9 Stock conversion for my G36 GBBR build, so i was wondering if i could make one, so here it is :)
This parts is dedicated for G39 IdZ Stock.

I've tried making it stand-alone, and i can make it but it required some hardware, and printed hinge for G36 Stock was a pain in my holes, as was the weakest part of the design.

Required buildplate size: 270x205mm (or bit smaller - Anycubic 4Max Pro bed size)

Todo:

  • cheek rest / cheek riser (that's why there are holes at the back), as G39-one is always too low for any optics.

Instruction:

  1. Take off the back part of the stock by rising stock setting lever (or however You call it)
    2 .put it between stock's front and back part,
  2. Put stock's back part back and lock it in place by setting lever.
    / if You are struggling with the lever just pull it out by removing pin, place the part in the stock and replace the lever with pin.

I can share my Fusion360 if You paypal me, as it took me just a little bit too much filament for prototyping, hope You understand. ;)
